  ."]},{"name":"Domesday Book","meanings":["1  English: relationship name from the Middle English personal name  <i>Bern</i>,  <i>Barn</i>. In the Midlands and East Anglia this is based on the Scandinavian personal name  <i>Biǫrn</i>, anglicized as  <i>Beorn</i>; in the south-west it is from Old English  <i>Beorn</i>; both names are from a word meaning ‘warrior’. Some of the following surname bearers may alternatively belong with other senses below.","2  English: status name from Middle English  <i>barn</i> (Old Scandinavian  <i>barn</i>) ‘child’. This term is found in   Domesday Book   as a byname for men of the upper classes; it might also have had the meaning ‘young man of a prominent family’, like Middle English  <i>child</i> (  see  Child  ).","3  English: locative name, nickname for residence near or employment at a barn, Middle English  <i>bern</i> (Old English  <i>bere-ærn</i>).  See also  Barnes  . Some of the post-medieval bearers may alternatively belong with (1) or (2)."]},{"name":"Buffey","meanings":["Norman, English:  see  Beaufoy  ."]},{"name":"Boffey","meanings":["Norman, English:  see  Beaufoy  ."]},{"name":"Boffy","meanings":["Norman, English:  see  Beaufoy  ."]},{"name":"Tengvik","meanings":["Norman, English: locative name from Eschalles in Pas-de-Calais (see   Tengvik  , p. 87)."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Robert De Beaufoy was born about 1310, in Foremark, Derbyshire, England, United Kingdom. He married Margaret Franceis. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. He died about 1356, in his hometown, at the age of 48."},"et":{"about 1310–about 1356":"umbes 1310–umbes 1356","1320–1344":"1320–1344","1344–1389":"1344–1389","1310–1356":"1310–1356","1356":"1356","1389":"1389","1344":"1344","1310":"1310","1320":"1320","about 1356":"umbes 1356","about 1310":"umbes 1310","Foremark, Derbyshire, England":"Foremark, Derbyshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"about 1310–about 1356":"noin 1310–noin 1356","1320–1344":"1320–1344","1344–1389":"1344–1389","1310–1356":"1310–1356","1356":"1356","1389":"1389","1344":"1344","1310":"1310","1320":"1320","about 1356":"noin 1356","about 1310":"noin 1310","Foremark, Derbyshire, England":"Foremark, Derbyshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","England":"Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"about 1310–about 1356":"environ 1310–environ 1356","1320–1344":"1320–1344","1344–1389":"1344–1389","1310–1356":"1310–1356","1356":"1356","1389":"1389","1344":"1344","1310":"1310","1320":"1320","about 1356":"environ 1356","about 1310":"environ 1310","Foremark, Derbyshire, England":"Foremark, Derbyshire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","England":"Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","lifeSummary":"Robert De Beaufoy est né environ 1310, à Foremark, Derbyshire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni. Il a épousé Margaret Franceis. Ils ont eu au moins 1 fille. Il est décédé environ 1356, dans sa ville natale, à l’âge de 48 ans."},"de":{"about 1310–about 1356":"um 1310–um 1356","1320–1344":"1320–1344","134